  "prompt": "What versions of the Bible are there?",
  "response": "There are numerous versions of the Bible, each catering to different needs and preferences. Here are some of the most well-known versions:\n\n1. **King James Version (KJV)** - Published in 1611, this is one of the oldest and most enduring translations.\n2. **New International Version (NIV)** - First published in 1978, this is a widely-used modern translation.\n3. **English Standard Version (ESV)** - Published in 2001, this version aims to be both accurate and readable.\n4. **New King James Version (NKJV)** - Published in 1982, it updates the language of the original KJV.\n5. **New American Standard Bible (NASB)** - First published in 1971, it is known for its literal accuracy.\n6. **New Revised Standard Version (NRSV)** - Published in 1989, it is widely accepted in academic circles.\n7. **The Message (MSG)** - A paraphrased version published in 2002, known for its contemporary language.\n8. **Christian Standard Bible (CSB)** - Published in 2017, it aims for a balance between readability and accuracy.\n9. **Revised Standard Version (RSV)** - Published in 1952, it was the first major revision of the American Standard Version.\n10. **Good News Bible (GNB)** - Also known as Today\u2019s English Version (TEV), first published in 1966, it uses simple, everyday language.\n11. **New Living Translation (NLT)** - First published in 1996, it is known for its clear and contemporary language.\n12. **Holman Christian Standard Bible (HCSB)** - Published in 2004, it aims for both accuracy and readability.\n13. **Amplified Bible (AMP)** - First published in 1965, it expands on the text to clarify meanings.\n14. **Contemporary English Version (CEV)** - Published in 1995, it aims for clarity and simplicity.\n\nThese are just a few examples, and there are many other translations available, each with its own strengths and unique characteristics.",
